  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Transfer duty, sometimes still referred to as stamp duty, is a state government tax charged on the transfer of property in Queensland. It is the buyer's cost, not the seller's, but sellers who understand how it works are better placed to read their buyer pool, anticipate negotiation dynamics, and price their property with a realistic picture of what buyers are actually spending to complete a purchase.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How transfer duty is calculated in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Transfer duty in Queensland is calculated on a tiered scale based on the purchase price of the property. The duty rate increases as the dutiable value rises. As a rough guide for 2026, a property purchased at $800,000 attracts approximately $28,000 to $30,000 in transfer duty for a buyer who does not qualify for any concession. A property at $1,200,000 attracts approximately $49,000 to $52,000. These are substantial costs that a buyer must fund in addition to the purchase price, and they come from the buyer's own resources since lenders typically do not include stamp duty in the loan amount.</p>

      <p>The Queensland Revenue Office publishes the current duty rates and provides an online calculator. The rates have been adjusted over time, and buyers should always verify the current figures with the OSR or their solicitor rather than relying on estimates from older sources or real estate commentary.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">First home concessions and how they affect your buyer pool</h2>
      <p>Queensland provides significant transfer duty concessions for first home buyers. A first home buyer purchasing a property valued at up to $700,000 to occupy as their principal place of residence pays no transfer duty at all. Between $700,000 and $800,000, a partial concession applies on a sliding scale. Above that threshold, the standard duty rate applies without concession.</p>

      <p>For sellers of properties in the $600,000 to $750,000 range, first home buyers are a meaningful segment of the buyer pool, and the duty concession is a genuine financial benefit that makes properties in that range more accessible. For sellers of inner-east Brisbane properties in the $900,000 to $1,500,000 range, the first home buyer concession is largely irrelevant because most buyers at those price points are either upgrading owner-occupiers or investors, neither of whom qualifies for the residential concession on those terms. Understanding which buyer types actually make up your realistic pool helps you interpret enquiry volumes and offer behaviour more accurately.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Home concessions for owner-occupiers</h2>
      <p>Beyond the first home buyer concession, Queensland also provides a home concession for buyers who intend to use the property as their principal place of residence and are not first home buyers. This concession reduces the duty rate compared to the standard rate paid by investors. The saving is meaningful: on an $800,000 purchase, the home concession reduces transfer duty by roughly $7,000 compared to the investor rate.</p>

      <p>For sellers, this distinction matters because owner-occupier buyers are paying less upfront in transaction costs than investors purchasing at the same price. An investor buying your property at $900,000 is paying several thousand dollars more in transfer duty than an owner-occupier at the same price. This affects the investor's total cost of acquisition and can influence how aggressively they negotiate relative to an owner-occupier buyer in the same bidding situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers need to understand buyer costs</h2>
      <p>Transfer duty affects your sale in several practical ways. First, it limits buying capacity. A buyer who has $1,000,000 available to spend on acquiring a property cannot offer $1,000,000 if they also need to fund $38,000 to $42,000 in transfer duty, legal fees, and other transaction costs. Their effective purchase budget for the property itself is closer to $950,000 to $960,000. Sellers who understand this dynamic set expectations more accurately and are less likely to misread buyer behaviour as bad faith when it is actually a reflection of total cost pressure.</p>

      <p>Second, transfer duty reinforces price sensitivities at certain thresholds. In markets where the first home buyer concession cuts off at $700,000, there is often elevated demand in the $650,000 to $700,000 range from buyers who want to maximise the concession. This does not directly affect the inner-east market for most property types, but it is worth understanding for smaller units or entry-level properties where first home buyers are a real presence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Is transfer duty ever a negotiation factor?</h2>
      <p>Transfer duty is the buyer's obligation under Queensland law. It is not a cost that sellers typically share or contribute to directly. However, in softer markets or unique negotiating situations, buyers occasionally attempt to use the size of their transfer duty bill as a reason for a price reduction, framing it as evidence that their total acquisition cost is high. This is not a sound basis for negotiating a lower sale price and most experienced sellers and agents will not accept the premise, but it helps to understand the argument before you encounter it.</p>

      <p>What can legitimately arise in negotiation is the settlement date. If a buyer is managing their cash flow carefully, partly due to the size of their transfer duty obligation, they may request a longer settlement period to give themselves time to organise funds. This is a reasonable request that costs you relatively little and can resolve an otherwise solid transaction without a price concession.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What this means for pricing your property</h2>
      <p>When you and your agent are setting your pricing strategy, the total cost of acquisition for a buyer at each price point is part of the picture. At $1,000,000, a buyer is paying approximately $38,000 to $42,000 in transfer duty on top of the purchase price. At $1,500,000, that figure is approximately $67,000 to $72,000. These are real numbers that constrain the effective buyer pool and help explain why buyer resistance sometimes appears at certain price thresholds even when comparable sales nominally support a higher price.</p>

      <p>Understanding transfer duty does not change the market value of your property, but it helps you understand why buyers behave the way they do at different price levels, and it gives you a more accurate picture of the financial position your buyer pool is actually in.</p>

